   Allied-Signal Debt Put
   On Review by S&amp;P
</HL>
<DATE>
12/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 27
</SO>
<CO>
   ALD
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
STOCK AND BOND RATINGS (RTG)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it is reviewing
the debt ratings of Allied-Signal Inc. with the possibility
of a downgrade.
   The review affects the ratings of Allied-Signal's single-A
senior debt, preliminary single-A Rule 415 shelf registration
senior debt and A-1 commercial paper. About $1.9 billion in
securities are involved, S&amp;P said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The credit-rating agency said it was taking the action
following a decision by Allied-Signal's 40%-owned Union Texas
Petroleum Holdings Inc. to discontinue efforts to sell the
entire company and instead place individual parts on the
auction block.
   S&amp;P said the move "creates uncertainty over timing and
value of potential proceeds." Allied-Signal was planning to
use the proceeds from the sale of Union Texas to reduce debt
incurred during its stock repurchase program.
</TEXT>
