<HL>
   Business Brief -- Carnival Cruise Lines Inc.:
   Company Estimates Profit
   Increased for Fiscal 1990
</HL>
<DATE>
12/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CCL
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Carnival Cruise Lines Inc. expects to report per-share
earnings for the fiscal year ended Nov. 30 of about $1.50 to
$1.55, up from $1.44 in the prior year, Micky Arison,
chairman and chief executive officer, said.
   For fiscal 1989, the Miami company had net income of
$193.6 million on revenue of $1.15 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Despite greater capacity -- this year the company has
added one new ship and a greater number of "berths," or beds,
on another -- Carnival's bookings are currently at about the
same percentage of occupancy as they were this time last
year, he said. He wouldn't be specific, however.
   The trouble spot was the company's resort and casino
business in Nassau, the Bahamas, which "performed below our
expectations," Mr. Arison said.
   Despite the weakening economy in the fourth quarter,
Carnival's occupancy rates, an important measure of a cruise
company's performance, were "approximately the same, maybe a
little better" than the year-ago quarter, Mr. Arison said.
</TEXT>
