<HL>
   International Brief -- Fokus Bank AS:
   Company Gets Equity Boost
   To Shore Up Loan Losses
</HL>
<DATE>
12/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   Fokus Bank AS, Norway's No. 3 bank, received an equity
injection of 1.5 billion Norwegian kroner (US$253 million)
from a national bank guarantee fund to shore up a capital
base eroded by soaring loan losses.
   The financial bail-out of Fokus Bank came only a day after
Norway's second biggest bank, Christiania Bank &amp; Kreditkasse,
disclosed that it now expects loan losses this year to more
than double and to plunge the bank to an operating loss of
nearly one billion kroner. Banking analysts said the loan
losses underlined continued weakness in the Norwegian
economy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fokus Bank blamed depressed real estate markets and a
collapse of the regional fish farming industry for a sharp
jump in nonperforming credits in its loan portfolio. The bank
expects to increase provisions against possible bad loans in
this year's accounts to 980 million kroner, more than wiping
out a 360 million kroner operating profit and leaving it with
a full-year operating loss of 600 million kroner.
   The guarantee fund's injection of guaranteed but not
paid-in equity capital will qualify as core capital and raise
the bank's capital ratio to 8.5%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ901224-0019
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
901224-0019.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Bridgestone Corp.:
   Japanese Tire Maker Lowers
   1990 Profit, Sales Estimates
</HL>
<DATE>
12/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 4
</SO>
<CO>
   J.BDT
</CO>
<IN>
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
</IN>
<LP>
   Bridgestone Corp. of Japan, a tire maker, lowered its
forecasts for 1990 net income and consolidated sales.
   Bridgestone said 1990 profit will amount to 10 billion yen
($74.1 million), which is off 50% from the company's initial
prediction in March of 20 billion yen. Sales are expected to
reach 1.78 trillion yen ($13.19 billion), or 1.1% less than
the initial forecast of 1.8 trillion yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In 1989, Bridgestone earned 9.6 billion yen on sales of
1.69 trillion yen.
   For its latest revision, Bridgestone cited soft market
conditions in North America and Europe, with weak customer
demand in the replacement-tire market and decreased new-auto
production. It said the lower forecasts also were prompted by
the suspension of natural rubber operations in Liberia, as a
result of that country's civil war, and increased production
costs owing to a rise in raw materials prices.
